Goal of the thread: Spend 5 minutes outside during the day.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

The OP is a WIP and any suggestions are appreciated.

For half a decade now, influential young scientists have denounced NASA’s decision to name its deep-space telescope after James E. Webb, who led the space agency to the cusp of the 1969 moon landing. This man, they insisted, was a homophobe who oversaw a purge of gay employees.

Hakeem Oluseyi, who is now the president of the National Society of Black Physicists, was sympathetic to these critics. Then he delved into archives and talked to historians and wrote a carefully sourced essay in Medium in 2021 that laid out his surprising findings.

“I can say conclusively,” Dr. Oluseyi wrote, “that there is zero evidence that Webb is guilty of the allegations against him.”

Critics called the NASA report “selective historical reading.” And they reframed their argument, saying that Mr. Webb should be held responsible for any anti-gay activity at NASA and at the State Department, where he had previously been a high-ranking official.

In a blog written with three fellow scientists, Chanda Prescod-Weinstein, a cosmologist at the University of New Hampshire with a low six-figure Twitter following, said that it was highly likely that Mr. Webb “knew exactly what was happening with security at his own agency during the height of the Cold War,” adding, “We are deeply concerned by the implication that managers are not responsible for homophobia.”

“This is about who we canonize and who are our real saints,” Dr. Prescod-Weinstein said in an interview. “We can’t just exonerate a dead white guy who was in the thick of a repressive government.”

I’ve thought about killing myself, My teenage years were spent praying for god every night to bring me death, thinking no one would ever touch me, never love me. I spent my 20s mistaking being throat fucked by the guy I loved and let live with me as affectionate waiting while he went on his real dates with his real girlfriends. I thought that’s all I could ever be good enough for, sitting there, thanking my lucky stars he ever even looked at me. I spent my life being the scapegoat for every fight my parents ever had, never measuring up to there expectations It wasn’t until I started loving myself, that I found out how beautiful a real healthy love with another person could be, and every day I spent not killing myself brought me closer to that.

Loving myself started very small, just the simple acceptance that I didn’t deserve to die just because I wasn’t wanted. That acceptance didn’t make me do everything I needed to do for myself right away but it was a start. I still have to work on it everyday, there’s always going to be something that comes up, someone who wants to bring you down, but I choose to live, everyday.

Your only guaranteed the life you got, and no one knows for sure what comes next. It’s up to you to make the most of it.

It’s your choice, just like it’s your choice to pick a handle like demon and go around hurting and pushing people away, but sharing the pain isn’t going to make it go away, it’s just going to hurt people who may want help, and what’s more it’s going to hurt people who need help, people just like you, because you are not alone in this fight, there are others.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>28813780
Yes-and-no.
It's plausible that they'd split into social groups based on secondary sexual characteristics, and that these groups would have different attributes, but implausible they would develop similarly to the ones we're familiar with in the contemporary western world, rather than contextually based on the circumstances faced in the lab.
But this applies to everything: If you made these lab-grown humans wear red and blue uniforms, red-vs-blue dynamics would quite probably overtake male-vs-female dynamics in terms of importance. If some got hats, and some didn't, you'd have overlapping uniform, headwear, and gender roles, and people might rank their relative importance differently as well.

The lesson I'd try to impart here is that human behavior is fundamentally group behavior. This isn't an abstract academic thing, it is very practical knowledge you can use in your daily life to understand why - for example - people will argue obviously insane things. It's usually not that they're insane, it's that they're showing loyalty to a given group which they are, or wish to be a member of. Then you know better than to engage, or to only engage in a way that surrounds the technical point you want to make with enough in-group language to make it palatable.

Adoption is a predatory industry built on stealing children from vulnerable women and their families. The best form of adoption is adoption within the family for several reasons, as many adopted children will express:
1. Medical history. Family medical history is often learned and passed by word of mouth. I wouldn’t know how to handle my eczema or IBS if my mom didn’t have the same issues and have developed habits she passed on that help.

This is also why if adoption must happen, it’s best to either have it occur within the biological family or have a fostering arrangement that allows family members to visit and help care for the adopted child.

2. Trauma. Adoption always always causes trauma. Even if you adopt very young, babies know who their biological mother is and crave her presence. And as children get older, the impact of adoption on the psyche can still lead to feelings of rage, isolation, etc. Even adopted children in families that love them still deal with this trauma their whole life.

3. You are not owed children, and it is selfish to assert you are. Children are agents with feelings, hopes, and preferences. It is natural for humans to prefer to not be adopted, I’m sorry but it’s true.

4. The industry targets vulnerable new mothers. There are literally adoption agents (and sometimes even prospective “parents”) who rather than providing support to new mothers and pregnant women, harass them into signing their child away, usually on the condition they never contact the child again and all the child’s records are changed.

5. Cultural history: humans have a need for culture, and adopted children not raised in the culture they were born into often experience isolation and trauma from not being able to identify with that culture, yet still often looking and even acting the part.

There are exceptions, and if you find yourself in a place where a child has no choice but to be adopted out, by all means
